Having extracted the rule, the natural question is whether it can be _iterated_ — whether applying it again and again to its own output produces a coherent infinite structure, a genuine fractal rhythm in the sense outlined in the chapter's introduction. The answer is negative, and the failure is immediately visible. Iterating the rule starting from $S L$ produces the sequence of words $S L, L S S, S S L L, L L S S S S, S S S S L L L L, dots$ — words in which the letters bunch together, all the $L$s on one side and all the $S$s on the other. The word $S S S S L L L L$ is not a rhythm in any meaningful sense: it is a block of four compressed pulses followed by a block of four expanded pulses, with no interleaving whatsoever. The rule has no mechanism for mixing the two letters within a single substitution step — wherever there is an $L$, it becomes $S S$ (a cluster of two identical shorts); wherever there is an $S$, it becomes $L$ (a single long, which will itself cluster at the next iteration). Structurally, the rule operates with only two states and oscillates permanently between them.

A second observation deserves mention before the diagnosis closes. In absolute units with $L = 2$ and $S = 1$, the successive words $S L, L S S, S S L L, L L S S S S, dots$ have lengths $3, 4, 6, 8, 12, 16, dots$, with consecutive ratios alternating strictly between $3:2$ and $4:3$. The iteration confines itself to the Pythagorean region of rhythmic proportion — octaves, fifths, fourths — and never accesses any ratio involving higher primes. The mirror rule shares this harmonic impoverishment with the elementary substitution $L arrow.r L L$, $S arrow.r S S$ that generates the nested doublings of the Western note-value system: both rules preserve inequality (for the mirror) or equality (for the elementary substitution) at every level, but neither escapes a narrow harmonic corridor. The mirror is one step above the elementary substitution — it does introduce inequality — but the step is small.

The failure can be made precise through an informal notion of _entropy_: the degree to which the two letters are interleaved across the word. A word with alternating letters, such as $S L S L dots$, has maximal entropy; a word with all shorts preceding all longs has minimal entropy. This notion is, up to a sign, the reciprocal of the potential energy of Section 3.1.3: words whose onsets cluster far from uniform spacing carry high potential energy and low entropy. The iterations of the mirror rule drive the entropy of their output monotonically toward its minimum.#footnote[The formal treatment of entropy for finite and infinite words, along with its relation to the Fisher information metric and to the topological entropy of substitution dynamical systems, is given in Book IV.]

The conclusion is sobering but structurally productive. The mirror rule of Section 3.2.2 is musically perfect at a single level: it generates the swung triplet from the swung duplet and preserves synchronicity across the entire morphing range. More than that: the consistency condition on the long–short ratio across one application of the rule, $r = 2 slash r$, yields $r = sqrt(2)$, in exact agreement with the tempering argument of @sec:tempering that identified $sqrt(2)$ as the meantone of the rhythmic domain — the ratio at which the balanced 50% swing position sits. The rule and the tempering are two readings of the same structural fact.#footnote[The formal derivation of $r = sqrt(2)$ as the positive solution of the consistency equation, together with its connection to the substitution's incidence matrix and the associated Perron–Frobenius framework, is given in @sec:ratio-equation of Book IV.] But the rule, iterated, does not manifest this ratio in the distribution of its output: the words it produces have the right asymptotic counts of $L$s and $S$s, but the letters are clustered rather than interleaved. The mirror rule has the right _ratio_ but not the right _distribution_. It is not a fractal rule. Iterated, it collapses into clustered blocks whose internal structure is harmonically poor and rhythmically inert.

If the programme outlined in this chapter's introduction is to succeed — a substitution rule that preserves the swing feel under indefinite iteration, producing a genuinely fractal rhythmic object at every scale — a different rule is needed, one that breaks out of the harmonic neighbourhood to which the mirror is confined, and whose consistency condition selects an irrational ratio with the structural depth to govern indefinite subdivision. What such a rule must look like, and what irrational proportion emerges from it, is the subject of the next section.

=== The Swinging Substitution: Fibonacci and the Golden Ratio

The failure of the mirror rule has a diagnosis that points toward its remedy. The rule $S arrow.r L$, $L arrow.r S S$ takes a long and replaces it with two shorts — two shorts that sit side by side, unmodified, at the deeper subdivision level. This is a conceptual slip. If the object under study is the swing, then a long that resolves into two equal shorts at the next level has lost its swing at that level. The subdivision has been refined, but the refinement itself is _straight_. It belongs to a different domain — the domain of the _elementary substitution_ $L arrow.r L L$, $S arrow.r S S$ that generates the nested doublings of the Western note-value system. The mirror rule shares with this elementary substitution the same structural limitation: whatever it produces at a finer level is no longer swung. It is, in the end, a straight subdivision dressed in swung symbols.

The remedy, once stated, is evident. If the rule is to remain within the domain of swing, it must swing the substituted material as well. Each long must be replaced not by two straight shorts, but by a _swung_ pair — a long followed by a short, or equivalently a short followed by a long. The rule becomes:
$
S arrow.r L, quad L arrow.r L S.
$
This small modification is, structurally, a large change. The pattern $L L$ at a given level no longer refines into $S S S S$ at the next, but into $L S L S$ — two swung duplets concatenated. Each long has become a miniature swung duplet, and the swing has propagated from one level to the next without interruption. The word is swung all the way down.

