Before pursuing the consequences, it is worth noting that the rule just written down is, in the combinatorial literature, the canonical _Fibonacci morphism_, and the infinite word it generates is the classical Fibonacci word, or _rabbit sequence_ — the most studied Sturmian word of the field.#footnote[References given in @sec:state-of-research: Noll 2008; Allouche & Johnson 2018; Berstel 2007; OEIS A003849. The Fibonacci morphism is a paradigmatic case in combinatorics on words. Its musical appearances — Nørgård's infinity series, Tom Johnson's _Narayana's Cows_, Noll's treatment of modes — are documented in the state-of-research. The formal identification with the rule above, together with the full spectral and dynamical properties, is developed in @sec:formal-setup of Book IV.] This identification — musical rule derived from a structural constraint on swing, mathematical object developed independently in combinatorics — is one of the surprising fruits of the present approach. The rule was not borrowed from the mathematical literature and applied to rhythm; it emerged from a musical requirement, and only then was recognised as an object already known for its exceptional properties.

The irrational proportion governing this rule emerges, as in the mirror case, from a _consistency condition_ — the requirement that the long-to-short ratio $r = L / S$ be preserved by a single application of the rule. Since $sigma(L) = L S$ and $sigma(S) = L$, the new ratio after substitution must equal the old ratio, which yields the quadratic $r^2 - r - 1 = 0$ whose positive root is the _golden ratio_:
$
r = phi.alt = (1 + sqrt(5)) / 2 approx 1.618.
$
Unlike the mirror rule, whose iterates alternated between clustered configurations, the iterates of the swinging substitution exhibit _interleaving_: shorts and longs alternate through the word without forming pure blocks of either letter. The distribution is homogeneous at every scale.#footnote[The derivation of the quadratic consistency equation, the eigenvalue analysis of the substitution's incidence matrix, and the proof that the Fibonacci word has exactly $n + 1$ distinct factors of length $n$ (the defining property of Sturmian words) are given in @sec:math-sturmian-fibonacci and @sec:ratio-equation of Book IV.]

The swing percentage associated with the golden ratio follows from the mapping between the linear swing scale and the logarithmic ratio scale — a mapping already established in @sec:tempering and consistent with the Weber–Fechner law of logarithmic perception. Under this mapping, a ratio $r$ corresponds to a swing of $log_2(r) times 100%$. Two checkpoints verify the mapping: $log_2(sqrt(2)) = 0.5$, so $sqrt(2)$ sits at 50% swing — the meantone of the tempering argument — and $log_2(2) = 1$, so the maximum swing of $2:1$ sits at 100%. The golden ratio gives $log_2(phi.alt) approx 0.694$, placing the Fibonacci swing at approximately 69.4%.#footnote[The full derivation of the logarithmic swing mapping, together with its perceptual justification via the Weber–Fechner law, is given in @sec:math-fibonacci-swing of Book IV.] This position lies between the 50% meantone and the 100% maximum, in the neighbourhood of the triplet-leaning zone characteristic of mainstream jazz swing — a structural fact rather than an empirical coincidence.

The consistency condition that yielded $phi.alt$ should be read carefully. It is not a limit reached asymptotically by the iteration, nor a statistical property emerging from long words. It is an _a priori structural requirement_: for the rule to produce a coherent swing at every level, the ratio must satisfy a condition that admits only one positive solution. The irrational number $phi.alt$ is not a curiosity that happens to appear; it is the unique proportion that makes the swinging substitution possible as a self-similar structure. In this sense, $phi.alt$ is to the swinging substitution what $sqrt(2)$ is to the mirror rule, and what the upcoming ternary extension will associate with the plastic ratio $rho$: each irrational proportion is the consistency condition of a specific substitution rule, the _only_ ratio at which that rule can be iterated without breaking the swing at some level.

Two further observations establish the contrast with the mirror rule, and their formal development is left to Book IV. First, the Fibonacci word has maximal entropy among infinite words on a binary alphabet — it achieves the tightest distribution of letters compatible with aperiodicity, and in this precise sense it sits at the theoretical limit of what a binary fractal rhythm can do.#footnote[This is the defining property of _Sturmian words_; a rigorous statement together with the associated combinatorial structure is given in @sec:math-sturmian-fibonacci of Book IV.] Where the mirror rule drove entropy toward its minimum, the swinging substitution sits at the theoretical maximum. Second, the harmonic neighbourhood of $phi.alt$ lies outside the Pythagorean corridor. The successive Fibonacci ratios $2 slash 1, 3 slash 2, 5 slash 3, 8 slash 5, 13 slash 8, 21 slash 13, dots$ approach $phi.alt$ from alternating directions, but none of them equals $phi.alt$ — each is a rational approximation, and $phi.alt$ resists rational approximation more obstinately than any other irrational. Musically, this places the golden-ratio swing in a harmonic position that no combination of octaves, fifths, and fourths can ever capture. It is a new neighbourhood, and the rule that generates it opens a region of the rhythmic continuum that the mirror rule — and _a fortiori_ the elementary substitution — could not reach.

The swinging substitution is therefore the first genuine fractal rule of this chapter. It preserves the swing at every level of iteration; it satisfies a consistency condition that selects a unique irrational proportion; it produces an infinite word of maximal entropy; and it occupies a harmonic neighbourhood distinct from the Pythagorean region in which the mirror is confined. Whether it is the only such rule on the binary alphabet, or whether other binary substitution rules satisfying analogous consistency conditions can be found — and what irrational proportions those rules would select — is the question of the next section.